  "filterintegrity|PQ|0": {
    "pre": [
      "Product-specific bacterial-retention validation plan; ASTM F838 method with B. diminuta (ATCC 19146).",
      "Worst-case product/process conditions and the product-wetted integrity limit defined."
    ],
    "steps": [
      "Under worst-case conditions (product matrix, max time, temperature), challenge the sterilizing-grade filter with B. diminuta at >= 1 x 10^7 CFU/cm2 of effective filter area (ASTM F838).",
      "Confirm the filtrate is sterile (full bacterial retention).",
      "Use the manufacturer correlation (bacterial challenge vs bubble point / diffusive flow, established across 3 lots x 3 filters) to set the max allowable diffusive flow / min allowable bubble point, with a safety margin; establish a product-wet correction where routine testing uses product not water.",
      "Confirm the routine integrity limit is at least as stringent as the validated correlation.",
      "Record retention and the correlated limit in the data table."
    ],
    "attach": "Bacterial-challenge (ASTM F838) data and the integrity-limit correlation.",
    "summary": {
      "cols": [
        "Parameter",
        "Measured",
        "Acceptance",
        "Result"
      ],
      "rowLabels": [
        "B. diminuta retention (sterile filtrate)",
        "Min allowable bubble point",
        "Max allowable diffusive flow"
      ]
    },
    "tableLabel": "Data table",
    "accept": [
      "Under worst-case product/process conditions the sterilizing-grade filter fully retains B. diminuta (ATCC 19146) challenged at >= 1 x 10^7 CFU/cm2 of effective area (sterile filtrate). Per ASTM F838-20.",
      "The non-destructive limit (product-wetted bubble point / diffusive flow) is correlated by the manufacturer to that retention (max allowable diffusion / min allowable bubble point, with a safety margin).",
      "The routine integrity limit applied in production is at least as stringent as the validated correlation.",
      "A product-wet correction factor is established where routine testing uses product rather than water.",
      "Integrity is tested before use (PUPSIT where required) AND after use, per Annex 1."
    ],
    "note": "Bacterial retention is the definition of sterilizing-grade; because the challenge is destructive it's done on the product/process (worst case), and the non-destructive integrity test is the routine surrogate - valid only because it's correlated to this B. diminuta result. The validation framework for sterilizing-grade liquid filtration is PDA TR 26 (Sterilizing Filtration of Liquids)."
  },
  "filterintegrity|OQ|4": {
    "pre": [
      "Filter assembly and the validated sterilization method (SIP or autoclave cycle) defined.",
      "Manufacturer's maximum sterilization-cycle rating and the product-correlated integrity limit on hand."
    ],
    "steps": [
      "Record the manufacturer's maximum validated number of sterilization cycles for this filter and the cycle conditions (e.g. 121-134 C steam, hold time).",
      "Subject the filter assembly to the required number of sterilization cycles - up to the worst-case maximum the process will apply - each at the validated cycle.",
      "After the cycles, wet the filter and run the integrity test (bubble point / diffusive flow / water intrusion as applicable).",
      "Confirm the result still passes at the product-correlated limit (the filter did not degrade).",
      "Record the cycle count and the post-cycle integrity result."
    ],
    "summary": {
      "cols": [
        "Sterilization cycle",
        "Conditions",
        "Post-cycle integrity result",
        "Limit",
        "Pass/Fail"
      ],
      "rowLabels": [
        "After cycle 1",
        "After mid cycle",
        "After max validated cycle",
        "Hydrophobic vent (WIT) if applicable"
      ]
    },
    "tableLabel": "Sterilization-cycle endurance",
    "accept": [
      "After the maximum validated number of sterilization cycles (SIP / autoclave at the validated temperature and hold time), the filter passes its integrity test at the product-correlated limit.",
      "The cycle count applied does not exceed the manufacturer's validated maximum.",
      "Any post-cycle drift toward the limit is characterised and stays within the limit."
    ],
    "note": "Filters are not indefinitely re-sterilizable - repeated steam sterilization can shift pore structure, so the manufacturer validates a maximum cycle count. This matters most for autoclave / SIP vent filters (typically hydrophobic PTFE, tested by water intrusion), which are sterilized repeatedly. Confirm the number against the filter validation guide; do not assume it."
  },
